  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and prison sentences. The specific penalties depend on the circumstances, but generally involve:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 10-20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n\n2. Monetary Penalties:\n- Fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential civil monetary penalties\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Increased scrutiny from financial regulators\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nThe exact penalties vary based on specific factors like transaction amount, intent, and prior criminal history. Prosecutors typically use statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act to pursue cases.\n\nI want to be clear that while I can discuss general legal information, I'm not providing specific legal advice. For precise details about a particular situation, consulting a qualified legal professional is recommended.",
